Alright, during the day I hung up the new nest box. This is how it looks in the garden.
But let's briefly recall. "What is inside, after all?" It seems no one has asked.
The top is an ESP32 camera board with a fisheye lens camera and an infrared LED light taken from a Raspberry Pi camera.
That peculiar plastic box shape is because the side panels of the nest box can rotate. When I bought it, it was like this and couldn't be modified, so I had to design it based on this condition.
Because there is no power supply in the garden, the entire device is powered by a solar panel and a 2600mAh 18650 lithium-ion battery.
I didn't take photos of the battery or charger, but here is the photo of the solar panel.
The gray box hanging on the side of the nest box contains the battery.
It can run for about 4 hours after being fully charged.
I call this a "special feature," so the birds can have a bit of privacy too.
